  &lt;p id="ajh7yN"&gt;Intel CEO Pat Gelsinger &lt;a href="https://www.intel.com/content/www/us/en/newsroom/news/intel-ceo-news-dec-2024.html"&gt;has retired&lt;/a&gt; after over four decades at the company and stepped down from the board of directors effective December 1st, 2024. Gelsinger rejoined Intel as CEO in February 2021, &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2021/1/13/22228702/intel-ceo-bob-swan-pat-gelsinger-technical-financial"&gt;taking over from Bob Swan&lt;/a&gt; to turn around the already struggling chipmaker — &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/4/2/24119454/intels-chipmaking-business-7-billion-loss"&gt;an effort that hasn’t gone as planned&lt;/a&gt;. It’s largely missed out on &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/1/24058186/ai-chips-meta-microsoft-google-nvidia"&gt;the AI chip boom&lt;/a&gt; that fueled Nvidia’s rise, failed to launch new technology on schedule, and &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/10/4/24262287/intel-13th-14th-gen-crash-raptor-lake-root-cause-fix"&gt;struggled&lt;/a&gt; with recent CPU instability issues.&lt;/p&gt;
